1 Setting Up a Report

RMarkdown is a development framework that can be used to generate documents in different formats - .html files, .pdf files, and slideshows using ioslides or slidy.

RMarkdown documents are created from a combination of two packages, included in Rstudio:

  • rmarkdown: processes markdown, generates output
  • knitr: runs Rcode and produces Markdown-like output

Lets walk through how to create a .Rmd file and its basic structure!

2 Integrating Markdown and R Code

Behold - an R code chunk below.

#I am a code chunk. I can be created using cmd+alt+i (or in a mac, cmd+opt+i)!
a <- 1+1 
a
## [1] 2
a*4
## [1] 8

What if you just want to show the output and hide the code?

## [1] "no problem! just specify the additional configuration option at the start of your code chunk! in this case, I used {r, echo=FALSE}"

Some options for configuring code chunks:

  • echo: when FALSE, code is not displayed
  • message: when FALSE, messages are not displayed
  • eval: when FALSE, output is displayed
  • include: when FALSE, neither code nor output is displayed
#Can you guess which configuration is being used here? 
1+1

Code can also be added inline. Here I am using this technique to multiply 3 by 2934, which equals 8802.

I can also reference the variable a I created earlier. Here I add a to 4 = 6.

3 Rendering Data and Visualizations in Reports

Now well discuss how to render dynamic, complex output using R Markdown.

3.1 Rendering Strings

## [1] "You can display a string like this"

or have it stored as a variable, then include the variable as an inline expression

or use the function cat with the configuration results = asis!

3.2 Rendering Markdown Lists

Markdown lists can be created in code chunks, then displayed inline.

#Method 1:making a list variable
ex_list <- "
- Lions
- Tigers
- Bears"

#Method 2:making a vector of animals then using code to make this a bulleted list

animals <- c("Lions", "Tigers","Bears")
test_list <- paste("-", animals, collapse = "\n")

Voila, our list using Method 1:

  • Lions
  • Tigers
  • Bears

And Method 2:

  • Lions
  • Tigers
  • Bears

Note: if you forget to include the r in you inline code, your result will look like this: ex_list

5 R Markdown in Action: Reporting on Life Expectancy

life_exp <- read.csv("~/Desktop/life_exp.csv")

# Which country had the longest life expectancy in 2015?
longest_le <- life_exp %>%
  filter(X2015 == max(X2015, na.rm = T)) %>%
  select(Country.Name, X2015) %>%
  mutate(expectancy = round(X2015, 1)) # rename and format column
longest_le 
##           Country.Name    X2015 expectancy
## 1 Hong Kong SAR, China 84.27805       84.3
# Which country had the shortest life expectancy in 2015?
shortest_le <- life_exp %>%
  filter(X2015 == min(X2015, na.rm = T)) %>%
  select(Country.Name, X2015) %>%
  mutate(expectancy = round(X2015, 1)) # rename and format column
shortest_le
##               Country.Name    X2015 expectancy
## 1 Central African Republic 51.37785       51.4
# Calculate range in life expectancies
le_difference <- longest_le$expectancy - shortest_le$expectancy
le_difference 
## [1] 32.9
# What are the 10 countries that experienced the greatest gain in life expectancy?
top_10_gain <- life_exp %>%
  mutate(gain = X2015 - X1960) %>%
  top_n(10, wt = gain) %>% # a handy dplyr function!
  arrange(-gain) %>%
  mutate(gain_formatted = paste(format(round(gain, 1), nsmall = 1), "years")) %>%
  select(Country.Name, gain_formatted)

# Join this data frame to a shapefile that describes how to draw each country
# The `rworldmap` package provides a helpful function for doing this
mapped_data <- joinCountryData2Map(
  life_exp,
  joinCode = "ISO3",
  nameJoinColumn = "Country.Code",
  mapResolution = "high"
)
## 214 codes from your data successfully matched countries in the map
## 50 codes from your data failed to match with a country code in the map
## 39 codes from the map weren't represented in your data

Data Summary

The data reveals the country with the longest life expectancy was Hong Kong SAR, China with a life expectancy of 84.3.
